\pard\keepn\sb100\sa100\b\fs36 Why the hell did they choose the 4th of July?\par
\pard\sb100\sa100\b0\fs24 By {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:jmdk@smac.ulaval.ca"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul Jean-Marie De Koninck}}}\cf0\ulnone\f1\fs24\par
\par
Listen to Jean-Marie De Koninck explain the Deep Impact mission (excerpt from an interview with Andr\'e9 Arthur on CKNU, June 21st 2005 - French only)\par
\par
Everyone remembers Comet Halley that flew very close to us in 1986. To be more precise, it came as close as 300 million kilometers from the Earth. It could then be observed with the naked eye due to its tail (the word \i comet\i0  comes from the latin \i coma\i0 , meaning hair of the head, due to the resemblance of a comet's tail to streaming hair.) spread over 100,000 kilometers and leaving a dust trail behind as long as a hundred kilometers. The european probe Giotto was launched towards the comet Hally on July 2nd 1985 and came 500 kilometers to it on March 14 1986.  Thanks to the images taken on this approach, scientists have been able to see the core of a comet fo the first time. Its composition still remains a mystery today.\par
Comet Halley takes 75 years to make a revolution around the sun. It will cross path with Earth again in 2061. Halley's comet is not the only comet in existence. On July 4 2005, the American probe Deep Impact will drop a 372 kg copper block on Comet Tempel 1. This collision will take place at a mere 133 million km from Earth. It is the first space mission with the goal to probe the insides of a comet.\par
Comet Tempel 1 was discovered in 1867 by Ernst Wilhelm Tempel. It is simply called Tempel 1 because another comet is called Tempel 2. A few years after its discovery, astronomers lost sight of Tempel 1 for ... a century. It was rediscovered in 1967. It orbits the sum with a 5.5 year period. Its exact size is still unknown because its core is not visible, athough images provided by the Hubble space telescope helped astronomers observe its ellongated shape and observe estimate its diameter to be about 6 kilometers.  \par
The fact that the surface of comets is made of ice and dust is already known, but to this day, the composition of their interior remains unknown. By carefully analyzing the impact produced on Tempel 1 at 1:52 on the morning of the 4 of July 2005, astronomers hope to learn more about its composition.\par
A team of 250 university professors, engineers, and managers have been busy preparing this mission for 6 years. The Deep Impact mission is a partnership between the University of Maryland, JPL (Jet Propuslion Laboratory, Pasadena, California), and Ball Aerospace and Technologies Corporation (Boulder, Colorado).\par
The Deep Impact probe left Earth on January 12 2005. It will take 173 days to reach the comet, after a 431 million kilometer journey. On the morning of July 3, a 1 meter cube 372 kg impactor will detach from the 976 kg probe. This impactor, also called SMART (for Self Monitoring Analysis and Reporting Technology) is for the most part made of copper, a material that should not be found inside a comet. During 22 hours, the main module and the impactor will be remotely controlled by the JPL navigators in California. Communication waves travelling at the speed of light, it will take about 7 minutes for a signal sent from Earth to reach the probe. 2 hours before the impact, SMART will switch into autonomous mode to find it's own way to the comet, which travels 1t 37,100 kilometers per hour or 10.3 kilometers per second. Before reaching its goal, SMART will have to navigate through a layer of debris emanating from the comet. These debris could damage the impactor and fail the entire mission. The main module will then be 500 km under the comet. It will have about 13 minutes to capture the images of the impact, before rushing into the comet's tail, using its shield to protect itself from the debris. On top of this module, more than 30 Earth-bound telescope will be observing the explosion.\par
It was calculated that the collision will not deflect the comet from its trajectory. In fact, one should not be afraid that the trajectory of Tempel 1 deflects towards the Earth, because it is estimated that the impact will only change its orbit by 10 meters, which corresponds to about 1 second out of a 5.5 year period. This is of minor importance in comparison with the 378 km deflection it will undergo when it will travel near Jupiter in 2024.\par
A few days ago, the engineers have realized that the main camera was out of focus. This was due to a fabrication defect of the telescope's mirror. It is not flat, it actually has a 15 kilometer radius of curvature (to be ideal, it should have an infinite radius of curvature!) To avoid this problem, the telescope should have been tested in a cryogenic tank, in vaccuum, and at temperatures as low as the temperatures in outer spaces. This type of test if overly expensive and the manufacturer had guaranteed that everything would function properly.\par
Amateur astronomers who will watch the images transmitted live from the probe will not notice the difference and will be well-served. However, scientists need exact images to be able to analyze them properly. This is where mathematicians come to the rescue. By using a mathematical transformation called deconvolution and agreat deal of computing time, the image captures by the space-bound camera will be corrected ... with a delay of a few hours.\par
As the 4th of July approaches, the mission engineer grow increasingly nervous. Reasons are numerous. One reason is the functionning of the impactor. It must be released from the main module 24 hours before the impact, that is 860,000 km from it target. SMART is supplied batteries to insure the functionning of all its electronic devices. It has a 24 hour autonomy. It is also supplied with a small quanty of fuel to direct its trajectory. Since the functioning of the impactor cannot be tested without releasing it and many problems may happen during those 24 hours, the engineers are now considering releasing the impactor only 10 hours before the impact. However, this scenario implies that the main probe would need to burn more fuel to avoid a collision with the comet. If it uses too much fuel, it will jeopardize the realization of its next mission; meeting another comet in three years.\par
Another problem can occur; it is possible that the impactor does not separate from the main module. In that scenario, the whole probe (the impactor attached to the main module) will be sent crashing on the comet. The NASA will then count on Earth-bound telescopes and those orbiting the Earth (Hubble and Spitzer) to observe the impact. It goes without saying that the images captured would not be as revealing. Another reason to wish that the mission takes place flawlessly!\par
You can find out by watching the impact live on the mission web site : {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://deepimpact.jpl.nasa.gov/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul deepimpact.jpl.nasa.gov}}}\cf0\ulnone\f1\fs24 . \par
But one question remains ; why the hell did the Americans choose the 4th of July for the impact?\par
